Heather and Solly live in Prudhoe, they no longer have any dependant children at home. Solly is a reasonably successful toilet paper manufacturer.  He was still working in  1998 when problems at work caused a delay on their holiday. Ruth, David and the children try to spend every other Christmas in Prudhoe. Solly is a keen supporter of Newcastle Football team (we don’t know his views on cricket). He is a quiet man with a garden shed, which he uses as a retreat.  He and his wife, Heather have come to Ambridge to help Ruth after the birth of both her children. When her parents are in Ambridge they stay in Brookfield Farm House.  Ruth is still very close to her mother, who writes her long and involved letters about what’s going on in the Pritchard family ( Ruth has cousins and uncles and aunts).Pip is very found of her maternal grandparents.Both parents are very proud of Ruth, (and of Solly’s success).  Their pride has on occasions embarrassed Ruth.

William Smethhurst wrote in The Archers, The Official
Companion: Dan Archer is the eldest of three sons born to
John and Phoebe Archer, tenant farmers on the 100-acre
Brookfield Farm, Ambridge.  After leaving the village school
he became a carter in the hay trade, helping at Brookfield,
of course, at ploughing, sowing and harvest, in 1916 he was
called up into the 16th battalion, The Borsetshire Regiment
and spent two years procuring hay for the army in France.
Then his father became seriously ill and he was discharged
and sent home to look after the farm.  In 1919 he was given
the tenancy of Weston Farm, a forty-one acre smallholding
and in 1921 he married Doris Forrest, the daughter of a
local gamekeeper.  When his father died, he and Doris were
given the tenancy of Brookfield (his brother Ben having
emigrated to Canada after fighting him for Doris, and Frank
having gone to seek his fortune in New Zealand).
Of their children, Jack tried his hand at farming but
eventually became Landlord of The Bull after marrying
Peggy Perkins of London; Christine is married to the game-
keeper on the Grey Gables Estate, George Barford and Phil
now runs Brookfield with his wife Jill and his son David.
In the Second World War, Dan was chairman of the local
agricultural committee, after the war he was a prominent
member of the tennis club, and in his later life he was
the chairman of the Parish Council.  He and Doris bought
Brookfield Farm in 1954 when Squire Lawson-Hope sold off the
estate, and in 1970 they retired to Glebe Cottage.
Doris died in 1981 and Dan died of a heart attack while
trying to help a ewe in April 1986 (He was out in the car
with Elizabeth at the time).  At 89 he was the second oldest
inhabitant of the Village of Ambridge, being four months
younger than Walter Gabriel.

In April 1966 there were several fires started deliberately around Ambridge. Villagers set up a fire watch, taking it in turns to guard the village. One evening Dan and Doris were at a party at Carol Grenville’s. Ned Larking was on fire duty.  
Ned went home for his supper and someone set fire to the outbuildings at Brookfield. Luckily Ned still had his wits about him and with Water’s help they were able to get the animals out. 
The next morning they discovered that the barn, pig house and machinery shed had been destroyed.
Gossip spread around the village that Dan had set light to the buildings himself. Because he had been intending to redevelop that part of the farm and had recently increased the insurance.  
For a month the identity of the culprit remained mystery, more people became the victims of the tittle-tattle; Fred Barratt, because he didn’t get on well with Ambridge Farmers, Johnny Martin because he liked to light camp fires in the woods and brew tea.    
One afternoon in May, Frank Mead was caught red handed trying to set fire to an outhouse at The Bull. He had always been a bit of an eccentric, anti drink and all kinds of entertainment, he disapproved of his daughter working in the pub, but no one believed him capable of such violence. 
Frank was committed to a mental hospital where he ended his days.

“So John Briar says - You’ll curse the day that you were born, squire and so will your children’s children……..
and the Squire he says, you leave this house, John Briar.  You leave this house and never darken my door again.
And John Briar, he goes off into the storm, with the pots and pans on his belt clanking and crashing, and he rages, and he curses, and he shakes his fists at the wind, and the rain.  He goes off into the night, and his missus, she don’t know where he is.  He finds  a little hovel next to the river, where the waters are rising and crashing of the waterfall drowns his cries, and he sits, and he thinks, and all he can think is Revenge Revenge!

Well, the night is long, and his missus, she’s beside herself with worry. So she gets the Village together, and they go a-searching for John. They search through the storm, with their lanterns swinging and the rain in their faces, and at last, they remember the hovel by the river, where the shepherd sleeps at lambing time, and down they go. The river’s running high, and the waterfall is crashing down onto the rocks below, and the water’s lapping at the door of the shepherd’s hovel.  And Sarah, she goes through the door, into that damp, dark place, and there’s John Briar, lying on the floor, with his face deathly pale.  And she lifts his head and says “John! John dear, it me. It’s Sarah!” and he opens his eyes, and looks at her, and he seems far away, like, and his cracked lips open, and he whispers to her. “Revenge! Revenge!”  And with a shudder, there in that dark hovel, he dies in her arms. But the river, and the waterfall, and the wind and the rain, all seem to take up that cry.  They cry for the wrong that the squire visited upon old John Briar.  And the cry seems to ring through the very air, growing louder and louder in the wind and the rain. Revenge! Revenge!   And under the noise of the storm and the river, there’s a clanking, and a clanking, and Sarah, she knows that noise too well.  And she’s fearful. She’s fearful for what the dawn may bring.

And up at the big house  they found the old squire dead in the morning with his hair turned white as snow.  Dead in the kitchen of his great house, with every pot and  pan in the place on the floor beside him.  Some said they’d heard a strange noise in the night, and it must have been the pots and pans falling.  And if some thought otherwise, they held their peace. But if you’re walking home on a dark November night and you hear the sound of pots and pans jingling behind you, don’t look back.  It might just be old John Briar…still a-looking for the Squire.”

Iftikar’s backstory
Iftikar Shah is the son of Pakistani Punjabi immigrants who arrived in the UK in the 1970s. His father was a self-made businessman who came to own a string of pound shops across Borsetshire.  All Ifty’s siblings are involved with the family business in some shape or form but Ifty’s a bit different, he’s always been the one to go against the grain and do his own thing.  Even as a child his social conscience was evident - he would steal Mother’s Pride from his dad’s shop and dole out slices to local tramps. 
He’s grown up in a chaotic, loving, extended family (the Borsetshire Shahs put the nouveau in nouveau riche!) and has inherited his father’s business brain.  However while he likes nice clothes and has a smart car, making money isn’t what he’s really about and he has made the choice not to work in the family business.  Ifty did a Maths and Business degree and now works as a maths teacher at a secondary school in Felpersham.  He also does some tutoring outside school.  While he was at University, Ifty did some youth work part-time.  He’s seen a lot of young Asian lads lose their way in life and he’s passionate about encouraging and supporting young people in any way he can. 
Ifty’s a bit of a lone wolf in his family, but he feels a strong obligation to his siblings and particularly to his mother who was widowed when he was a teenager.  His mother would like to see him settle down and has in the past nagged him to scour online Asian dating sites, but he’s always refused.  Now as the years are passing, she’d be happy to see him bring home anyone at all!
The truth is handsome Ifty has his pick of girls but he’s a commitment phobe.  He’s by no means a rat though, he’s always up front and honest about his intentions.  This doesn’t put women off however and he’s had a lot of short-term girlfriends.  Moreover he’s got an idealised image of Mrs Right, and is waiting for someone who he deems to be perfect.
